<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910124-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910124-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Smith Is Reassigned   To New Job at United   Telecommunications</HL><DATE>01/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   WNEWS UT GTE</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- United Telecommunications Inc., struggling toregain the momentum lost in last year's long-distance phonewars, reassigned the national accounts chief at its US SprintCommunications Co. unit to a public relations and qualitycontrol job and revamped its entire marketing operation.   Sprint has fallen behind its rivals American Telephone andamp;Telegraph Co. and MCI Communications Corp. in signing up bigcorporate customers and has been losing ground in theresidential market as well.</LP><TEXT>   Named to the new post of senior vice president for qualitydevelopment and public relations at United was Richard C.Smith, who used to oversee all of Sprint's sales andmarketing. Now he is in charge of quality, corporatecommunications, community relations, the Corporate Foundationand the University of Excellence.   A spokeswoman said the move was not a demotion. Was it apromotion? &quot;No. I don't think so,&quot; she said. &quot;It would be alateral {move}.&quot;   United Chairman William T. Esrey said in a statement thatMr. Smith's appointment &quot;underscores {United's} total qualityprogram and our ongoing commitment to attracting the bestemployees and developing them to their full potential.&quot;   Sprint also realigned its marketing, sales and supportfunctions into four market segment business units --residential, small and medium business, major accounts andinternational.   Tom Weigman, Sprint's chief marketing officer, a newposition, is in charge of &quot;overall market definition, brandpositioning, product management and technology planning.&quot; Heis also an outsider, having been a senior partner withMarketing Corp. of America in Westport, Conn.   In addition, Sprint broke its business into four groups:Consumer Services, residential phone customers; BusinessServices, small to medium businesses; Major Accounts, bigcorporations; and a National Service Organization will handlecustomer service for residential and small-to-medium-sizedbusinesses as well as operator and conferencing services.</TEXT></DOC>